  "prompt": "How many grams of sugar should I eat in a day/week if I have cancer?",
  "response": "The recommended sugar intake for cancer patients varies depending on individual health conditions, type of cancer, and treatment. However, generally:\n\n1. Most health experts recommend limiting added sugar intake to:\n- Less than 25-36 grams (6-9 teaspoons) per day for adults\n- Less than 10% of total daily calories from added sugars\n\n2. For cancer patients specifically:\n- Consult with your oncologist or registered dietitian\n- They can provide personalized advice based on your:\n  * Cancer type\n  * Treatment plan\n  * Overall health\n  * Nutritional needs\n\n3. General guidelines for cancer patients:\n- Focus on whole, nutrient-dense foods\n- Minimize processed and refined sugars\n- Choose complex carbohydrates\n- Maintain a balanced diet\n\n4. Some studies suggest that high sugar intake may:\n- Potentially fuel cancer cell growth\n- Impact immune function\n- Contribute to inflammation\n\nAlways consult your healthcare team for personalized nutritional guidance during cancer treatment, as individual needs can vary significantly.",
